Product Information

4th Generation
30-Round Capacity
High visibility indicator in MagLevel window shows rounds remaining in mag
Anti-Tilt Follower and Stainless Steel Spring Impact cover stores on bottom of magazine (with standard floorplates)

Available in Black, Flat Dark Earth, Foliage Green and Olive Drab

The MagPul Gen 4 MagLevel PMag is constructed from advanced polymers with superior impact resistance and light weight. The 30-round magazine features a constant curve interior profile for improved feeding. An anti-tilt follower and high quality stainless steel spring ensure reliable feeding. The textured magazine body and flared floorplate improved handling over standard magazines. The Pmag is designed to lock into place reliably on a closed bolt with a full 30 rounds, unlike standard magazines which are generally down-loaded to 28 rounds. The snap-on impact cover protects the feed lips from impacts and debris while in storage. The impact cover also allows loaded magazines to be stored long-term (over 1 year) without compromising the integrity of the feed lips. The design of the floor plate is simple to disassemble using the impact cover or simple punch for cleaning and maintenance. The magazine will accept PMag accessories, such as Maritime floor Plates and PMag Ranger Plates. Available in four molded-in colors, Black, Flat Dark Earth, Foliage Green and Olive Drab.

The MagLevel features two clear windows molded into the magazine body, and a specific coil of the mag spring painted orange to indicate the round count. When the mag is fully loaded the brass cartridges are visible, when there are 25-rounds remaining the Round Indicator will become visible, tracking the rounds down to zero. The mag body has 25, 15, and 5 molded in to correspond with the MagLevel Indicator. The indicator allows you to see the round count while the mag is locked in the weapon, something that is not possible with transparent mags on the market.

This is a Webley Kaufmann .455 caliber D.A. revolver. Between 1878 and 1881 P. Webley & Son was associated with Kaufmann. On the left side you will see the triangle with Michael Kaufmann’s stylized initials MK with in it and #697 below it. This one was made about 1884 or 1885. This is a second model and was sold in the Army & Navy Co-operative stores. The bore is bright and shinny with strong rifling and the mechanical function is crisp and tight. This was purchased around 1966 from a Webley collector and was rarely fired.

title: For Sale:  WWI French Ruby
postcontent: Here's your chance to own a relic of the Great War. For sale is a Spanish ruby contract pistol manufactured for the French for trench warfare. There are no import marks, so it appears to be a bring back. Manufactured by Gabilandos, which was the prime contractor of the Ruby. Shows all the signs of heavy trench use. Pistol is pitted, with a light patina. There is a decent amount of bluing left. It has been completely disassembled and dipped to prevent further pitting. At this point, it's more of a display piece and very occasional shooter. These were infamous for being just as dangerous to the person behind the gun as it was to those who it was pointed at. Add 100 years of aging to that. It had feed issues the one time I fired it, but I found out it had the wrong magazine. I have since sourced the correct one.
